1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
What is rocket science really?

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:07,000
In the beginning, God created the heaven and the earth.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,000
In this special episode of American Alchemy,

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:14,000
we're going to pull on all of the threads of this hidden history.

5
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Sex magic, Nazi scientists, secret societies, launch rituals,

6
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:22,000
rockets launched in time with pagan festivals,

7
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:26,000
Walt Disney's hidden messages.

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,000
This is the story of how communication with non-human intelligence

9
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
might just be the real and hidden foundation of our entire journey to the stars.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,000
The whole subplot of our modern space program.

11
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:50,000
The date is July 16th, 1969.

12
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:56,000
Two hundred and thirty thousand miles away from home

13
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,000
sat NASA astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin.

14
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Columbia Houston, you're looking great.

15
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:04,000
Just two and a half hours before,

16
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,000
they had become the first pilots to touch down on another world.

17
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:10,000
The vehicle has landed.

18
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,000
As they prepared for their first moonwalk,

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Buzz Aldrin opened a small kit of personal items that he had brought with him.

20
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:24,000
Aldrin then proceeded to carry out the first religious ceremony ever conducted on the moon.

21
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:30,000
Using a small silver chalice, a bit of wine, and a piece of bread that he had brought with him,

22
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:32,000
he quietly administered communion.

23
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:38,000
He recalled the wine curling slowly and gracefully up the side of the cup.

24
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:44,000
It was interesting to think the very first liquid ever poured on the moon was communion wine.

25
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:50,000
That's one small step for man, one giant leap for Freemasonry.

26
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:53,000
Does the landing on the moon have anything to do with Masonry?

27
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:55,000
Yahoo! Go to you!

28
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:03,000
Among his belongings was a small silk flag hand-stitched with the symbol of the Scottish Rite of Freemasonry.

29
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
According to the Masonic Grand Lodge of Ohio,

30
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:12,000
the Apollo 11 mission even established an appendant body of the Masonic Lodge on the moon.

31
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:17,000
That flag is now on full display at the Masonic Temple in Washington, D.C.

32
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
When man reaches new worlds, Masonry will be there.

33
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:30,000
The Scottish Rite is a branch of Freemasonry steeped in esoteric symbols, ritual, and mysticism.

34
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Its highest rank, the 33rd degree, is symbolically tied to the 33 vertebrae of the spine,

35
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:41,000
culminating in the crown chakra, said to be the gateway to divine insight.

36
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
Buzz Aldrin, as it happens, held that rank.

37
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:54,000
Over the years, researchers looking at these kinds of oddities began to ask questions about the meaning of these rituals on the moon.

38
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:58,000
But those answers are not exactly what we're trying to explore in this episode.

39
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:05,000
What I'm interested in is the hidden side of NASA and the even more secretive National Reconnaissance Office, or NRO.

40
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:10,000
Agencies that have quietly launched thousands of rockets and payloads into orbit.

41
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:13,000
Behind them lies a stranger history than most people realize.

42
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:21,000
Because after all, Buzz Aldrin was not the first nor the last member of NASA to bring what some might derisively call the woo

43
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:27,000
to the epitome of nuts and bolts aerospace, astrophysics, and rocket fuel.

44
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:33,000
Just take Edgar Mitchell, Apollo 14 astronaut, the sixth man to walk on the moon,

45
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:38,000
in one of the most outspoken voices linking space exploration with the paranormal.

46
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:45,000
Mitchell wasn't shy about his belief in extraterrestrial life, or that the US government was probably covering it up.

47
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:53,000
But beyond the UFO question, he was also deeply invested in consciousness and the psychic phenomena.

48
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:00,000
On his journey to the moon, Mitchell conducted a private ESP, or extrasensory perception experiment,

49
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:05,000
attempting to send mental images back to Earth using a set of cards.

50
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,000
The results, scored by colleagues back on Earth, were better than chance.

51
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
Mitchell wasn't shy about this.

52
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:15,000
In a 1971 New York Times interview, he said,

53
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
We're too much uninformed about telepathy or ESP to project its uses.

54
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:26,000
But I think, once we understand the mechanism, then we can start talking about uses.

55
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:30,000
Few at NASA were interested, except one.

56
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:31,000
Werner Von Braun.

57
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:36,000
War is a dirty business, and all I can say is that I'm happy that it's all over now.

58
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
Yes, that Von Braun, former Nazi and father of American rocketry.

59
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:49,000
He was, according to Mitchell, deeply supportive, even encouraging Mitchell to find a site within NASA to study consciousness further.

60
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:59,000
After his mission, Mitchell founded the Institute of Noetic Sciences, a think tank dedicated to consciousness, psychic phenomena, and metaphysics.

61
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Von Braun attended one of its early fundraising dinners.

62
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:07,000
For Mitchell, the overview effect, seeing Earth from space, was spiritual.

63
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:11,000
It made him wonder if the entire cosmos might be conscious.

64
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And he wasn't alone.

65
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
There I was.

66
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
And there you are.

67
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
There you are, the Earth, dynamic, overwhelming.

68
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:26,000
And I felt that the world was just, just too much purpose, too much logic.

69
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:29,000
It was just too beautiful to have happened by accident.

70
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:33,000
There has to be somebody bigger than you and bigger than me.

71
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:37,000
And I mean this in a spiritual sense, not a religious sense.

72
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:45,000
There has to be a creator of the universe who stands above the religions that we ourselves create to govern our lives.

73
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
From the early days of rocketry to the height of the Apollo program,

74
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,000
there's been a long tradition of visionary scientists who saw no contradiction between physics and mysticism.

75
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Even today, the pattern continues.

76
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:02,000
They're using the images of Roman gods.

77
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
And I would ask him, I said, why are you using the images of Roman gods?

78
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:12,000
Why are you putting them on your mission patches and also utilizing Latin phrases from that time period?

79
00:06:12,000 --> 00:06:14,000
I mean, you're sending it up into space.

80
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
Who up in space is going to read Latin?

81
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:23,000
And his answer was, our sponsors.

82
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:31,000
Behind rocket technology, the thrust, the telemetry, the hardware, there is something else, something older.

83
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:35,000
There are whispers and subtle acknowledgements to gods.

84
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:41,000
Ancient symbols, rituals, and perhaps even the influence of non-human intelligence.

85
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:46,000
And if that is true, or at least if people involved in this science believe it to be true,

86
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:51,000
then we need to ask the fundamental question, what is rocket science really?

87
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:58,000
Is it foundationally entangled in something very strange we've spent millennia trying to understand?

88
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
Are there strange forces helping us get off this planet?

89
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:09,000
So buckle up, alchemists, because this one is going way out there.

90
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:31,000
When we think about the moon landing, the rockets, the computers, the broadcasts sent across two hundred and thirty

91
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,000
thousand miles of empty space.

92
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:41,000
It's easy to forget how recent this kind of knowledge really is.

93
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:47,000
Just over a century ago, astronomers were still debating the basic structure of the universe.

94
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:53,000
Einstein had shaken the foundations of physics in 1915 with his general theory of relativity.

95
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:01,000
But when it came to the cosmos itself, even the experts weren't sure what they were actually looking at through their telescopes.

96
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:11,000
Then, in 1923, Edwin Hubble peered through the 100-inch Hooker Telescope at Mount Wilson Observatory and saw something staggering.

97
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:21,000
This new telescope was powerful enough to resolve individual stars inside what most had assumed was just a cloud of gas in our own galaxy.

98
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:30,000
Guess what? It wasn't. That cloud, Andromeda, was another galaxy entirely, millions of light-years away.

99
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:39,000
This discovery shattered the old view. Our Milky Way wasn't the whole universe. It was just one among many.

100
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:53,000
It changed the cosmic perspective of the 20th century in the same way Copernicus had centuries earlier when he removed the Earth from the center of the solar system.

101
00:08:53,000 --> 00:09:03,000
And the man who built this observatory that made this discovery possible was one of the most important and strangest figures in the history of modern astronomy.

102
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:09,000
I bring you George Ellery Hale.

103
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:15,000
Hale wasn't just a brilliant physicist. He was a visionary, and in some ways, a mystic.

104
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:25,000
While still at MIT, he invented the spectro-heliograph, a device that could capture solar flares erupting from the sun's surface.

105
00:09:25,000 --> 00:09:29,000
But Hale's fascination with the sun went far beyond science.

106
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:36,000
He saw astronomy as a kind of philosophy, a link back to ancient Greece, Mesopotamia, Egypt, and Babylon.

107
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:41,000
He founded multiple observatories, including Mount Wilson in Pasadena.

108
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:47,000
The lodges where astronomers stayed were reportedly decorated with Egyptian hieroglyphs and symbols.

109
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:55,000
A reminder that they weren't just studying the stars. They were joining a tradition as old as human civilization.

110
00:09:55,000 --> 00:10:04,000
Then there's the stranger part. Hale claimed he received creative inspiration from a being, an elf, or a spirit, as he described it.

111
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:09,000
Some biographers wrote this off as stress, eccentricity, or mistranslation.

112
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:10,000
But what if it wasn't?

113
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:17,000
Hale certainly wasn't the first, or the last, brilliant scientist to feel like he was receiving messages from somewhere else.

114
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:20,000
His reverence for the sun wasn't just theoretical.

115
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:29,000
When he designed the Hale Solar Laboratory in Pasadena, he included a tribute to Ankh-Aten and the arch above the entrance.

116
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:35,000
The ancient Egyptian pharaoh who tried to replace the entire Egyptian pantheon with a single god.

117
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:37,000
Atem, the sun disk.

118
00:10:37,000 --> 00:10:42,000
When Hale died, his obituaries called him a priest of the sun.

119
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:44,000
A modern Zoroaster.

120
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:50,000
You might think Hale's beliefs were just personal quirks, unrelated to his science.

121
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
But this fits a much larger pattern.

122
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:03,000
Throughout history, the people we celebrate for pure science, the mathematicians, the engineers, the astronomers, were often described as tapping into something else.

123
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:08,000
Something they themselves called mystical, spiritual, or supernatural.

124
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:12,000
Today, we like to separate the discovery from the discoverer.

125
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
We want breakthroughs to feel rational, mechanical, explainable.

126
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:23,000
But that doesn't erase the fact that many of those breakthroughs were made by people who believed they were channeling something deeper.

127
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:32,000
Back in the early 20th century, Hale's work to help lay the foundations for modern astronomy.

128
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:35,000
But his influence didn't stop with telescopes.

129
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:44,000
He also transformed a small technical school, Throop Polytechnic, into what would become a powerhouse of science and engineering.

130
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Caltech.

131
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:51,000
By the 1930s, Caltech was more than just a hub for equations and experiments.

132
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:54,000
It became a magnet for the greatest minds on Earth.

133
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:01,000
Hubble, Bohr, Oppenheimer, Heisenberg, even Einstein passed through its halls.

134
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:04,000
But Caltech also attracted outsiders.

135
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:06,000
One of them wasn't even a student.

136
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:13,000
But he would end up reshaping the future of American rocketry and possibly opening a door to something far stranger.

137
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:16,000
Jack Parsons.

