171
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:27,000
John Whiteside Parsons, Jack to his friends, was born in Pasadena in 1914.

172
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:30,000
From an early age, he was hooked on science fiction.

173
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:34,000
He struggled in school and never earned a formal degree.

174
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,000
But that didn't matter.

175
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:40,000
Parsons had an intuitive genius for chemistry and propulsion.

176
00:14:40,000 --> 00:14:48,000
As a teenager, he and his friend Ed Foreman built homemade rockets, scavenging parts from Foreman's father's workshop.

177
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:54,000
One classmate later described them as a couple of powder monkeys going out into the desert, blowing things up.

178
00:14:54,000 --> 00:15:00,000
Jack's mother, worried about his obsession with explosives, sent him to military school.

179
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:03,000
He was expelled after he blew up a toilet block.

180
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:05,000
Nothing deterred him.

181
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:07,000
Parsons had one dream.

182
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:09,000
To build a machine that could reach the moon.

183
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:20,000
By the early 1930s, he and Foreman were sneaking onto the Caltech campus to meet like-minded students who believed in rocketry.

184
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:28,000
Just a few years earlier, a Caltech student named Thomas Townsend Brown had formulated a less crude version of space travel.

185
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:34,000
But that fell upon deaf ears with top physics professors at Caltech like Robert Milliken.

186
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,000
Parsons was able to gain much more traction.

187
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:46,000
He found an ally in Frank Molina, an engineering student working under Theodore Von Carmen, one of the sharpest minds in aerodynamics.

188
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:56,000
Together, they formed an informal rocketry group and began testing experimental engines in the Arroyo Seco, a dry gulch just outside Pasadena.

189
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:02,000
That site would later become Jet Propulsion Laboratory, JPL.

190
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:06,000
Now here's something a lot of people don't realize.

191
00:16:06,000 --> 00:16:11,000
At about 24 miles altitude, the first stage breaks away and the second stage motors fire.

192
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:18,000
In the early 20th century, even some of the most respected physicists believed rockets wouldn't work in space.

193
00:16:18,000 --> 00:16:28,000
One of them, Caltech's own Fritz Zwicky, the man who coined the term supernova and theorized dark matter, dismissed the idea as nonsense.

194
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:31,000
They misunderstood Newton.

195
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:37,000
They thought rockets needed something to push against, and in the vacuum of space, there would be nothing to push on.

196
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
Even the New York Times mocked the idea in a 1920 editorial.

197
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:48,000
So when people like Jack Parsons pursued this, they weren't solving a hard problem.

198
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:51,000
They were chasing what many thought was a delusion.

199
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:54,000
That makes what they achieved all the more remarkable.

200
00:16:54,000 --> 00:16:58,000
They believed in the impossible, then figured out how to build it.

201
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:04,000
And Parsons, as we'll see, believed in more than just exotic propulsion.

202
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:14,000
At Caltech, his raw intuition led to breakthroughs in both solid and liquid fuels, more powerful and reliable than anything that had come before.

203
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:20,000
The tests were chaotic and dangerous, but soon the military took notice.

204
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:29,000
Parsons developed a solid fuel booster, or what would later become the first stage of a rocket, to help heavily loaded aircraft take off.

205
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:33,000
They called it Jet Assisted Takeoff, or JADO.

206
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:40,000
They avoided using the word rocket because it still sounded too much like science fiction.

207
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:43,000
The first successful JADO flight was in 1941.

208
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:49,000
By 1942, the US military was ordering 20,000 units per month.

209
00:17:53,000 --> 00:17:58,000
But just as JPL was taking off, the FBI came knocking.

210
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:01,000
Because Jack Parsons wasn't just a rocket scientist.

211
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:04,000
He was also a practicing occultist.

212
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:16,000
He was a devoted member of the Ordo Templi Orientis, or OTO, an esoteric order led at the time by the infamous Aleister Crowley.

213
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:27,000
Thelema, their belief system, combined ceremonial magic, Eastern mysticism, and tantric techniques into what Crowley called sex magic.

214
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:31,000
That's magic with a K, to distinguish it from stage tricks.

215
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:34,000
Parsons wasn't just a casual participant.

216
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:42,000
He led the local chapter from a Pasadena mansion where he lived with a rotating cast of artists, intellectuals, and magicians.

217
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:51,000
The rituals were elaborate, invoking gods, spirits, and forces said to reside in higher dimensions.

218
00:18:51,000 --> 00:19:00,000
The most infamous of these was the Babylon Working, an attempt to summon the divine feminine archetype known as Babylon.

219
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:09,000
Inspired by Crowley's novel Moon Child, the ritual aimed to recreate a magical child through spiritual and sexual practices.

220
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:13,000
Not literal birth, but transformation of the self.

221
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:30,000
Kind of a weird extracurricular for a guy who became known as the father of the American space program.

222
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:36,000
These weren't acts of fantasy to Parsons.

223
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:39,000
He believed the rituals had real power.

224
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:46,000
That they could raise consciousness, open doorways, and make contact with non-human intelligences.

225
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:49,000
He wasn't alone in thinking this way.

226
00:19:49,000 --> 00:20:03,000
Gnostic Christian sects, early mystics like Clement of Alexandria, and Tantric traditions in India and China all described sex as a vehicle for divine communion.

227
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:06,000
Not lust, but willful transformation.

228
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:09,000
Parsons believed he was continuing that lineage.

229
00:20:11,000 --> 00:20:13,000
But it gets weirder.

230
00:20:13,000 --> 00:20:18,000
His ritual partner for the Babylon Working was a man named L. Ron Hubbard.

231
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:21,000
Yes, that L. Ron Hubbard.

232
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:27,000
Before founding Scientology, Hubbard helped Parsons conduct the ritual series.

233
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:32,000
But soon after, he ran off with Parsons' girlfriend and a chunk of his money.

234
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:41,000
Parsons, furious, attempted a magical counterattack, invoking the spirit of Mars, Bartzabel, in a Miami hotel room.

235
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:44,000
Magic or not, Parsons got his compensation.

236
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:51,000
Hubbard's yacht would promptly encounter a storm, and a court later forced him to pay Parsons back.

237
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:56,000
After that, some began to wonder if the Babylon Working had actually succeeded.

238
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,000
If it had opened something up in 1946.

239
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:06,000
Because in the years that followed, reports of unidentified aerial phenomena began to skyrocket.

240
00:21:06,000 --> 00:21:09,000
Parsons himself believed he had made contact.

241
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:13,000
He said he was being guided by non-human intelligence.

242
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:16,000
That idea surfaces in Diana Pasolka's work as well.

243
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:24,000
The notion that visionary scientists may have been receiving messages, insights, or downloads from something beyond.

244
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:32,000
It also is a prominent theme in Professor Jimena Canales' book, Bedeviled, about the history of demons and science.

245
00:21:32,000 --> 00:21:34,000
Parsons wasn't alone in this belief.

246
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:42,000
Pythagoras, Newton, and even Edison spoke of mystical inspiration or communion with unseen forces.

247
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:49,000
Edison, near the end of his life, actually tried to build a device to communicate with the dead.

248
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:54,000
So even if we keep our skeptic hats on, we're left with this strange pattern.

249
00:21:54,000 --> 00:22:02,000
Many of the people responsible for scientific breakthroughs, people we call geniuses, didn't see themselves as inventors.

250
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:05,000
They saw themselves as receivers.

251
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:15,000
In Parsons' case, he believed he was building technology to carry humanity into space, with the help of something else.

252
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:20,000
He would sometimes recite Crowley's hymn to Pan during rocket tests.

253
00:22:22,000 --> 00:22:33,000
According to legendary French UFO researcher Jacques Vallée, there were rumors of a ritual in the Mojave, where a blonde woman appeared and claimed to be from Venus.

254
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:45,000
If true, this would have been the first recorded encounter with a quote-unquote Nordic, or tall white, non-human entity, predating similar contactee stories by years.

255
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:52,000
Eventually, Parsons' occult lifestyle, strange houseguests, and growing paranoia led to trouble.

256
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:55,000
He was pushed out of JPL.

257
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:00,000
In 1952, he died in an explosion in his home laboratory.

258
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:05,000
Officially, it was ruled an accident involving volatile chemicals.

259
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:08,000
But some found the circumstances suspicious.

260
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:15,000
Parsons left a crater on Earth, but also one on the Moon.

261
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:16,000
Literally.

262
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:18,000
A lunar crater now bears his name.

263
00:23:18,000 --> 00:23:23,000
And at JPL, some insiders still call it, Jack Parsons Laboratory.

264
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:26,000
Others just say, Jack Parsons Lives.

265
00:23:26,000 --> 00:23:31,000
Now you might be thinking, sure, there was one eccentric rocket guy with a thing for ritual magic.

266
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:35,000
Maybe he laid the groundwork for ICBMs and Apollo.

267
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:37,000
But that doesn't mean that the whole field was weird.

268
00:23:37,000 --> 00:23:38,000
Maybe.

269
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:39,000
Maybe.

270
00:23:53,000 --> 00:24:00,000
Longtime viewers of this show will know we've covered evidence linking the Third Reich to UFO technology before.

271
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
From reports that Hitler knew about the 1933 Magenta crash.

272
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:10,000
To rumors of Nazi saucer tests in modern-day Czechoslovakia.

273
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:16,000
To the post-war absorption of German rocket scientists experimenting with exotic propulsion.

274
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:24,000
But what often surprises people isn't just the tech.

275
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:30,000
It's the fact that the highest level of Hitler's regime were obsessed with the occult.

276
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:32,000
This wasn't just Hollywood fantasy.

277
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:36,000
Sure, Indiana Jones gave us Nazis hunting for the Ark of the Covenant.

278
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:38,000
But the truth is stranger.

279
00:24:39,000 --> 00:24:48,000
In 1945, near the end of the war, American forces uncovered a hidden stash of Nazi documents in a cave in southern Germany.

280
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:53,000
Among them were records, revealing real state-sponsored occult projects.

281
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:57,000
Expeditions to Tibet to trace Aryan origins.

282
00:24:57,000 --> 00:25:05,000
Searches for ancient runestones, pagan sites, and even a government-backed quest to find the Holy Grail.

283
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:13,000
A lot of this stemmed from Heinrich Himmler, head of the SS and one of the architects of the Holocaust.

284
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:18,000
He was obsessed with Germanic mythology, paganism, and mystical power.

285
00:25:18,000 --> 00:25:28,000
He turned Wellesburg Castle into a ritual center, complete with a black sun chamber beneath it and a round table for his SS knights.

286
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:39,000
He also created the Anna Nürbe, a pseudoscientific institute devoted to proving that the so-called Aryan race descended from Atlantis.

287
00:25:39,000 --> 00:25:42,000
And yes, they actually believed that.

288
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:54,000
The Nazi Party itself was born out of the Thule Society, a Volkish secret group that mixed Germanic paganism, Atlantis myths, and Aryan esotericism.

289
00:25:54,000 --> 00:26:05,000
The Thule Society held seances and rituals meant to contact non-human intelligences they believed were their ancient progenitors.

290
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
Star beings from the far north, beneath the Polestar.

291
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:14,000
They performed these rites at symbolic locations, like the Harts Mountains.

292
00:26:14,000 --> 00:26:21,000
On nights like Walpurgisnot, a festival tied to witches, spirits, and old pagan ceremonies.

293
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:32,000
There are also claims about the Vril Society, a group said to have channeled anti-gravity technology and psychic powers from an ancient subterranean race.

294
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:39,000
Now, we don't have to believe any of these occult theories themselves, but what matters is the Nazis did.

295
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:41,000
And it didn't just stop at mysticism.

296
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
The Nazis were also pioneers of actual rocket science.

297
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:49,000
One of the key figures was Hermann Oberth.

298
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:57,000
Born in Transylvania, inspired by sci-fi writer Jules Verne, Oberth began theorizing about spaceflight as a teenager.

299
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:09,000
In 1923, he published The Rocket into Planetary Space, a landmark book that laid out how a multi-stage rocket could escape Earth's gravity.

300
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:12,000
He was decades ahead of his time.

301
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:19,000
He envisioned orbiting telescopes, spacesuits, weather-controlling satellites, even missions to other planets.

302
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:29,000
His ideas sparked a movement, and when World War II began, Oberth was pulled into military work, building rockets for Germany and later for Italy.

303
00:27:30,000 --> 00:27:37,000
After the war, Oberth became one of the few major scientists to publicly support the reality of UFOs.

304
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:49,000
After so many witnesses have seen the so-called flying saucers, their existence cannot longer be denied.

305
00:27:49,000 --> 00:27:55,000
I believe that these flying objects come from another solar system.

306
00:27:56,000 --> 00:28:03,000
In a 1954 lecture, he argued that these UFOs had been observed since at least the 1400s.

307
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:10,000
Oberth believed they were piloted by extraterrestrial visitors, monitoring Earth's nuclear sites and military tech.

308
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:13,000
In interviews, he even said,

309
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:18,000
We cannot take all of the credit for our record advancements in certain scientific fields.

310
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:20,000
We have been helped.

311
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:22,000
When asked by whom, he replied,

312
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:24,000
The people of the other worlds.

313
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:35,000
Later in life, Oberth was invited to watch the launch of Apollo 11 and the space shuttle Challenger.

314
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:40,000
But he wasn't part of the official Operation Paperclip transfer of Nazi scientists.

315
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:45,000
That honor fell to his most famous student, Werner Von Braun.

