344
00:30:09,000 --> 00:30:11,000
Now back to the episode.

345
00:30:11,000 --> 00:30:17,000
Dr. Von Braun, were you embarrassed to come to London this time after being responsible for the V-weapons during the war?

346
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:28,000
I'm really happy to have this opportunity to express my personal sympathies to those in London who lost their loved ones in these V-weapon raids.

347
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:31,000
But then war is a dirty business.

348
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:34,000
And all I can say is that I'm happy that it's all over now.

349
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,000
Von Braun wasn't just a German rocket scientist.

350
00:30:37,000 --> 00:30:46,000
He was the architect of the V-2 missile program, a major in the SS and one of the top minds in Hitler's war machine.

351
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
Like Parsons, Von Braun had dreamed of space since he was a boy.

352
00:30:50,000 --> 00:31:00,000
But where Parsons was invoking goddesses in desert rituals, Von Braun was swearing loyalty to Himmler and building rockets with slave labor from concentration camps.

353
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:11,000
After the war, the U.S. swept Von Braun up in Operation Paperclip, a covert mission to extract Nazi scientists.

354
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:18,000
He was captured in Bavaria, where a young Henry Kissinger was actually helping run counterintelligence for the United States.

355
00:31:18,000 --> 00:31:22,000
Von Braun's record was scrubbed and he was given a new job.

356
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:25,000
Build America's space program.

357
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And that he did.

358
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:36,000
Von Braun became the public face of NASA, a media darling, the man behind the Saturn V rocket that took us to the moon.

359
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:43,000
But the overall size and weight of the rocket is mainly determined by the 11 tons weight of this top section.

360
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:54,000
This weight dictates the amount of fuel and the numbers of motors needed to produce enough power to equalize the gravitational pull of the Earth.

361
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:04,000
But behind the scenes, many of the ideas, the scientists, and even the weirdness of the Nazi space program had been brought into the American one.

362
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:07,000
As we'll see, the weirdness didn't vanish.

363
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:09,000
It just changed uniforms.

364
00:32:09,000 --> 00:32:16,000
But before we get to NASA's more esoteric side, we need to check in with the other major player in the space race.

365
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:39,000
Before Parsons, NASA, or the Nazis, another conception of human purpose, one tied to our place in the universe, was emerging in late 19th century Russia.

366
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:44,000
Something we now call Russian cosmism.

367
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:56,000
It began with a librarian and philosopher named Nikolai Fyodorov, who believed the true task of humanity and Christianity was not to await resurrection, but to cause it.

368
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:03,000
He believed that one day, technology would allow us to resurrect every human who had ever lived.

369
00:33:03,000 --> 00:33:11,000
And that once death was defeated, humanity's next task would be to colonize the cosmos.

370
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:21,000
Among those most influenced by Fyodorov and his ideas was a deaf, self-taught young man named Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.

371
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:25,000
He would become known as the father of Russian spaceflight.

372
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:29,000
Tsiolkovsky didn't just believe space travel was possible.

373
00:33:29,000 --> 00:33:31,000
He believed it was necessary.

374
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:38,000
He saw humanity as part of a cosmic process, destined to leave Earth and populate the stars.

375
00:33:38,000 --> 00:33:44,000
In 1903, he developed what we now call the Tsiolkovsky rocket equation.

376
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:51,000
The fundamental formula describing how a rocket accelerates based on its mass and exhaust velocity.

377
00:33:51,000 --> 00:33:59,000
Like Oberth, he anticipated breakthroughs in rocketry and space exploration well before they were technologically feasible.

378
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:02,000
And here's where things get especially strange.

379
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:09,000
As Diana Pasolka points out in American Cosmic, Tsiolkovsky believed that non-human intelligences,

380
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:15,000
what he called ethereal beings, were communicating with us through celestial symbols.

381
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:16,000
He wrote,

382
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:23,000
We are made as the ethereal beings, existing beyond our dimensions of recognized reality.

383
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:32,000
These higher beings are in communication with us, reading our thoughts and sending us messages through celestial symbols,

384
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:36,000
which most of us do not even perceive, much less understand.

385
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:46,000
A genius is one who comprehends and channels these messages from higher beings into technologies, products and even art.

386
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:53,000
Tsiolkovsky seemed to believe that his rocket science, the very math that would take humans off Earth,

387
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:57,000
was received through this kind of cosmic transmission.

388
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:04,000
He may have seen himself not only as an engineer, but as a medium for an intelligence beyond human understanding.

389
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:11,000
Another example of someone who saw the spiritual dimension of science as fundamental to the work itself.

390
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:20,000
Even as the Soviet Union officially rejected religion, it opened the door to a different kind of cosmic mythology,

391
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:28,000
one in which ancient contact with extraterrestrials was treated not as fantasy, but as a legitimate scientific possibility.

392
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:33,000
These ideas were often framed in speculative or scientific language,

393
00:35:33,000 --> 00:35:45,000
a political workaround that allowed Soviet thinkers to explore humanity's possible contact with advanced extraterrestrial civilizations without invoking the supernatural.

394
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:53,000
Figures like Alexander Kazantsev and Felix Ziegel proposed that alien visitors may have influenced early human development,

395
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:59,000
seeding myths and technologies that were later taken on by ancient cultures.

396
00:35:59,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Unlike in the West, where such theories were typically fringe, in the USSR they were sometimes discussed in academic circles,

397
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:13,000
covered in state-run media, and even investigated by military and intelligence services.

398
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:24,000
This made paleocontact, as they called it, not just a conspiracy theory, but a semi-legitimate line of inquiry into humanity's cosmic origins.

399
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:28,000
But it was the Americans who won the space race when they made it to the moon.

400
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:36,000
And maybe, just maybe, that mission carried within it a hidden reverence for the esoteric dimensions of spaceflight

401
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:41,000
that men like Tsiolkovsky and Fyodorov had long envisioned.

402
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:47,000
Maybe the space race wasn't just a Cold War pissing contest, but a transcendental mission.

403
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:52,000
Which brings us to NASA, where the weird gets even weirder.

404
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:11,000
NASA was officially established on July 29th, 1958, by the National Aeronautics and Space Act.

405
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:17,000
On paper, this document laid out that NASA was supposed to be a civilian agency for space exploration,

406
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:22,000
devoted to quote-unquote peaceful purposes for the benefit of all mankind.

407
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:26,000
But that idealism is tempered in the very next paragraph.

408
00:37:26,000 --> 00:37:33,000
The act makes clear that the general welfare and security of the United States requires such an organization.

409
00:37:33,000 --> 00:37:45,000
And that any activities, peculiar to or primarily associated with weapons systems, military operations, or the defense of the United States, fall outside the civilian mandate.

410
00:37:45,000 --> 00:37:59,000
In practice, that meant if NASA found anything deemed strategically sensitive, at all, a breakthrough in propulsion, a powerful new sensor, or even contact with non-human intelligence, it could be withheld indefinitely.

411
00:37:59,000 --> 00:38:03,000
It's a reminder of something we've talked about before.

412
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:07,000
The echoes of the 1954 Atomic Energy Act.

413
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:20,000
If you read the definition of special nuclear material in the Public Atomic Energy Act of 1954, it basically states any material that releases any kind of atomic energy.

414
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:22,000
That would be retrieved crash material.

415
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:24,000
So it's kind of a sneaky way.

416
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:25,000
No, it is.

417
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:34,000
If you actually read the Atomic Energy Act, if something is not a nuke, but it has radiological energy coming off it, you know, alpha, beta decay, whatever.

418
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:35,000
Same secrecy.

419
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:36,000
Same secrecy.

420
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:38,000
How did the Nazi rocket scientists get in?

421
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:46,000
After Operation Paperclip, Werner Von Braun and his team were brought into the U.S. to work on ballistic missiles.

422
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:54,000
Many of them ended up in places like Fort Bliss in White Sands, where they were housed in military camps and worked under tight control.

423
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:00,000
Swastikas and Nazi memorabilia were reportedly on open display in some of these facilities.

424
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:09,000
FBI documents even showed that at one point Von Braun was caught sending classified documents to his Nazi counterparts in the USSR.

425
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:12,000
But it seemed like no disciplinary action was ever taken.

426
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:22,000
During this period Von Braun caught the attention of Walt Disney.

427
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:27,000
The two collaborated on a series of educational films about space exploration.

428
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:37,000
Von Braun features a lot in them, explaining the future of space exploration and the capabilities of imagined rockets and space stations.

429
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:43,000
One extended scene, a team of astronauts travel to the far side of the moon for the first time.

430
00:39:43,000 --> 00:39:51,000
That's when a radar engineer yells out that some kind of radiation is being picked up on their sensors at 33 degrees.

431
00:39:51,000 --> 00:39:56,000
Something that turns out to be a very constructed looking feature on the terrain of the moon.

432
00:39:56,000 --> 00:39:58,000
Get some flares in that area, quick.

433
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:17,000
The film moves on without too much attention being paid to the set of ruins on the moon.

434
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:21,000
Almost like it was just included for those that would notice it.

435
00:40:21,000 --> 00:40:26,000
Perhaps it was just a coincidence, an imaginative nod to the unknowns of space.

436
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:29,000
The coordinates, 33 degrees, are hard to ignore.

437
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:34,000
Especially given the prominence of that number in the Scottish Rite of Freemasonry.

438
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:40,000
There are a few Scottish Rite Masons you might have heard of.

439
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:44,000
And those that were awarded the highest honor of becoming a 33rd degree.

440
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:51,000
This includes the first American to orbit the Earth, John Glenn, as well as the President, Harry Truman.

441
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:55,000
And another astronaut we've already discussed, Buzz Aldrin.

442
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:59,000
James Webb, NASA Administrator, Scottish Rite Mason.

443
00:40:59,000 --> 00:41:03,000
Kenneth Kleinecht, Director of Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo.

444
00:41:03,000 --> 00:41:05,000
Also a Scottish Rite Mason.

445
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:08,000
We've also got Leroy Gordon Cooper Jr.

446
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:10,000
Who flew on the Mercury and Gemini programs.

447
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:13,000
And then you have Walter Shura Jr.

448
00:41:13,000 --> 00:41:15,000
And Don Eisel, who flew on Apollo 7.

449
00:41:15,000 --> 00:41:19,000
As well as Virgil Grissom, who flew on the Mercury program.

450
00:41:19,000 --> 00:41:23,000
But sadly passed away in the training capsule fire for the first Apollo mission.

451
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:26,000
Thomas Patton Stafford flew Apollo 10.

452
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:28,000
All Freemasons.

453
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:33,000
Later, on Apollo 15, the eighth person to walk on the moon was also a Mason.

454
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:34,000
James Irwin.

455
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:36,000
And another man we've already mentioned earlier.

456
00:41:36,000 --> 00:41:42,000
Edgar Mitchell, who spent more than nine hours walking on the moon's surface on Apollo 14.

457
00:41:42,000 --> 00:41:44,000
Freemason.

458
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:50,000
So by the mid-1960s, the structure of NASA, and I mean the actual power structure,

459
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:55,000
was a strange cocktail of former SS officers, Freemasons, and occultists.

460
00:41:55,000 --> 00:41:59,000
And then there's the Teos Cave story.

461
00:41:59,000 --> 00:42:00,000
You know where I do want to go though?

462
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:03,000
You know, there are all the conspiracies that the moon landing was faked.

463
00:42:03,000 --> 00:42:08,000
And then there's the UFO conspiracy that Neil Armstrong saw, like, UFOs on the moon or whatever.

464
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:10,000
I'm not proposing that. I don't necessarily think that that's true.

465
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:19,000
But the one possibly kind of funny piece of additional evidence would be that the second expedition Neil Armstrong did was in 1975.

466
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:23,000
And it was to a cave in Ecuador at the edge of the Amazon.

467
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:25,000
And it was called the Teos Cave.

468
00:42:25,000 --> 00:42:29,000
And it was supposed to contain ancient alien metallic artifacts.

469
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:40,000
And so clearly, Neil Armstrong believed enough in the possibility of that thing to, like, go into the Amazon and risk his life and try to look for it.

470
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:43,000
And a BBC documentary crew followed him in there.

471
00:42:43,000 --> 00:43:08,000
What we've seen throughout this video is that there's something more than a sterile materialist view of reality behind the engineering and physics of space exploration.

472
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:12,000
There seems to be a kind of ritual element to it.

473
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:19,000
And one of the clearest signs that NASA wasn't just about nuts and bolts science is something hiding in plain sight.

474
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:21,000
The mission patches.

475
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:24,000
Take the official Apollo program patch.

476
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:26,000
At first glance, it's simple.

477
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:31,000
The Earth, the moon, a path connecting them and a large letter A.

478
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:32,000
But look again.

479
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:35,000
Behind the A is the constellation Orion.

480
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:40,000
And the crossbar of the A is deliberately aligned with Orion's belt.

481
00:43:40,000 --> 00:43:44,000
The three stars, Mintaka, Alnilam, and Alnitak.

482
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:47,000
In Greek myth, Orion is the hunter.

483
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:51,000
But to the ancient Egyptians, those three stars were Osiris.

484
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:55,000
God of the afterlife, death, and resurrection.

485
00:43:55,000 --> 00:43:59,000
And in the patch, they're outlined in blue, given special emphasis.

486
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Strange, right?

487
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:06,000
Especially for a mission named after Apollo, the Greek god of the sun.

488
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:12,000
Why name the mission after one deity but center its symbolism around an entirely different pantheon?

489
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:15,000
And which pantheon are we talking about here?

490
00:44:15,000 --> 00:44:17,000
Was the big A for Apollo?

491
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:21,000
Or for Assar, the Egyptian name for Osiris?

492
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:29,000
In Egyptian myth, Osiris is murdered by his brother Set and resurrected by his wife Isis and their son Horus.

493
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:32,000
Who then defeats Set and restores cosmic order.

494
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:37,000
A myth of death, rebirth, and celestial destiny written into the sky.

495
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:44,000
NASA's primary launch pad at White Sands, where von Braun ran early tests, was Launch Pad 33.

496
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:46,000
Same thing at Kennedy Space Center.

497
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:47,000
There's only one runway.

498
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:50,000
And it isn't runway 1 or A.

499
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:52,000
It's runway 33.

500
00:44:52,000 --> 00:44:55,000
Even key mission planners had surprising backgrounds.

501
00:44:55,000 --> 00:45:01,000
Farouk El-Baz, who oversaw lunar science planning and helped select Apollo landing sites,

502
00:45:01,000 --> 00:45:04,000
was nicknamed the king by the astronauts.

503
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:07,000
His father was a scholar of Egyptian religion.

504
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:11,000
And of course, NASA was never shy about a little syncretism.

505
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:15,000
They would mix and mash and pay homage to all sorts of ancient traditions.

506
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:21,000
Juno, the Roman queen of the gods, lent her name to one of the earliest launch vehicles.

507
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:26,000
Mercury, the Roman messenger god, was chosen for the first human spaceflight program.

508
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:29,000
Then came Gemini, the zodiac twins.

509
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:34,000
And finally, Apollo, the Greek sun god of light, knowledge, and rebirth.

510
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:41,000
One of the most intriguing aspects of the whole story is how the symbolism doesn't stop at names or patches.

511
00:45:41,000 --> 00:45:45,000
It carries into the actual timing of the launches themselves.

512
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:55,000
Back in 1936, while Jack Parsons was still testing rockets in the Arroyo Seco,

513
00:45:55,000 --> 00:46:00,000
his team managed their first successful liquid fuel test on Halloween night.

514
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:04,000
That date, October 31st, was originally Samhain,

515
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:10,000
a pagan festival marking the midpoint between the autumn equinox and the winter solstice.

516
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:16,000
Over 20 years later, Explorer 1, the first U.S. satellite built by JPL,

517
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:21,000
was launched on January 31st, 1958.

518
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:24,000
That day is known in the Christian calendar as Candlemas,

519
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:27,000
but in the pagan tradition as Imbolc.

520
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:32,000
The odds of the U.S. space program being bookended by Samhain and Candlemas,

521
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:38,000
two cross-quarter days with deep ritual significance in European pagan tradition, are striking.

522
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:44,000
Even if not consciously planned by the engineers, the timing seems to follow an occult template.

523
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:49,000
Samhain as a symbolic gateway, and Candlemas as a moment of rebirth.

524
00:46:49,000 --> 00:46:52,000
Together, they framed the dawn of American spaceflight.

525
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:54,000
But we're just getting started.

526
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:57,000
This alignment with sacred dates was not a one-off.

527
00:46:57,000 --> 00:47:01,000
During the Apollo era, launch planners sometimes chose dates

528
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:04,000
that aligned with celestial or symbolic turning points.

529
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:10,000
One of the clearest examples was Apollo 8, the first crude orbit of the moon.

530
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:15,000
It launched on December 21st, 1968, the winter solstice,

531
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:20,000
the day the sun is symbolically reborn after the longest night of the year.

532
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:25,000
Apollo 8 marked the first time humans left Earth's gravitational field.

533
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:30,000
And from lunar orbit, the crew delivered the famous Genesis reading on Christmas Eve.

534
00:47:30,000 --> 00:47:34,000
In the beginning, God created the heaven and the earth.

535
00:47:34,000 --> 00:47:38,000
And the earth was without form, and void.

536
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:41,000
And darkness was upon the face of the deep.

537
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:45,000
And the Spirit of God moved upon the face of the waters.

538
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:49,000
And God said, let there be light.

539
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:51,000
And there was light.

540
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:54,000
And God saw the light, that it was good.

541
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:57,000
God divided the light from the darkness.

542
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:00,000
But was it just convenient scheduling?

543
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:03,000
Or was some deeper archetypal pattern playing out?

544
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:06,000
A subconscious script of death and resurrection?

545
00:48:06,000 --> 00:48:08,000
I'm going to give a little warning here.

546
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:10,000
What I'm going to lay out next is highly speculative.

547
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:12,000
I'm not saying I definitely believe it.

548
00:48:12,000 --> 00:48:14,000
And it might sound a little bit out there.

549
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:16,000
Let's take Apollo 11 as an example.

550
00:48:16,000 --> 00:48:26,000
Launched on July 16th, 1969, it coincided with the 24th anniversary of the Trinity Atomic Test.

551
00:48:26,000 --> 00:48:28,000
The dawn of the nuclear age.

552
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:34,000
But the moon landing itself on July 20th happened under the astrological sign of Aquarius.

553
00:48:34,000 --> 00:48:38,000
Symbol of the water bearer and bringer of knowledge.

554
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:42,000
Aquarius is often linked with enlightenment and radical change.

555
00:48:42,000 --> 00:48:49,000
And it's tempting to think that the moon landing, timed as it was, might have been more than a technological milestone.

556
00:48:49,000 --> 00:48:53,000
It could have been seen as a ritual passage into a new cosmic age.

557
00:48:53,000 --> 00:48:56,000
The so-called Age of Aquarius.

558
00:48:56,000 --> 00:49:01,000
Remember, Aldrin poured wine into a silver chalice during his private communion ceremony on the moon.

559
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:06,000
Humanity, in a sense, poured itself into another world.

560
00:49:06,000 --> 00:49:10,000
What's especially fascinating is that these symbolic alignments haven't gone away.

561
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:13,000
They've continued into the 21st century.

562
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:18,000
In a presentation, former CIA officer John Ramirez described one particular case.

563
00:49:18,000 --> 00:49:22,000
The 2005 launch of NRL 16.

564
00:49:22,000 --> 00:49:24,000
The mission patch was strange.

565
00:49:24,000 --> 00:49:31,000
It showed a pelican, a sun, several pentagrams, a silhouette of Bigfoot and palm trees.

566
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:39,000
Ramirez said that the pelican caught his attention because it matched the aviary codename of CIA scientist Ron Pandolfi.

567
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:44,000
Pandolfi has been a mysterious figure long tied to the UFO topic.

568
00:49:44,000 --> 00:49:53,000
He has worked on exotic physics, was connected to the Jasons and Mitre Corporation, and was part of the CIA's Office of Scientific and Weapons Research.

569
00:49:53,000 --> 00:49:57,000
A lot of people say that Pandolfi works the CIA's Weird Desk.

570
00:49:57,000 --> 00:50:04,000
According to Ramirez, Pandolfi was directly involved in this NRL 16 launch.

571
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:09,000
The launch itself happened on 1250 AM on April 30th, 2005.

572
00:50:09,000 --> 00:50:18,000
This happens to be the same day of Walbur Gisnacht, the traditional pagan holiday tied to the idea of gates opening between worlds.

573
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:28,000
The vehicle carried a payload named Prometheus, launched on a Titan IV rocket, and headed northeast towards the constellation of the Big Dipper.

574
00:50:28,000 --> 00:50:36,000
This alignment has uncanny parallels to a ritual described in the 1977 grimoire known as the Necronomicon.

575
00:50:36,000 --> 00:50:48,000
According to the text, the best time to perform the ceremony of walking, a kind of spiritual journey to the stars, is when the great bear hangs by its tail in the sky.

576
00:50:48,000 --> 00:50:57,000
The ritual is said to work best around midnight, facing north, with specific emphasis on the northeast, the direction the Big Dipper rises.

577
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:06,000
The number five is the sacred, and the launch occurred at 050, five years into the millennium, on a patch covered in five pentagrams.

578
00:51:06,000 --> 00:51:07,000
One.

579
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:20,000
Some researchers, like Peter Lavenda, have suggested that figures close to these launches encouraged people like Tom DeLonge to study Greek mythology.

580
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:26,000
Especially the story of Prometheus, to better understand the UFO phenomena.

581
00:51:26,000 --> 00:51:31,000
That name, of course, matched the payload on the NRL-16.

582
00:51:31,000 --> 00:51:35,000
After the launch, the remaining Titan IV rockets were retired.

583
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:40,000
One went to the National Museum of the U.S. Air Force at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base.

584
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:47,000
The other went to McMinnville, Oregon, the site of one of the most famous UFO photographs ever taken in 1950.

585
00:51:47,000 --> 00:51:51,000
All slightly schizo-coincidences? Maybe.

586
00:51:51,000 --> 00:52:00,000
But Lavenda has said that he's personally received letters from inside the U.S. military, praising the Necronomicon for being quote-unquote spot-on.

587
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:04,000
Including some from officers in Strategic Air Command.

588
00:52:04,000 --> 00:52:08,000
For years, his book was even a bestseller at Fort Benning.

589
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:10,000
In just a few minutes, we're going to be left.

590
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:13,000
Annual surge, plus 400,000 vacationers.

591
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:16,000
Then there's the symbolism of the Big Dipper itself.

592
00:52:16,000 --> 00:52:26,000
In Spielberg's Close Encounters of the Third Kind, the first UFOs to appear above Devil's Tower formed the shape of the Dipper in the sky.

593
00:52:26,000 --> 00:52:33,000
Jacques Vallée noted that Betty Hill's abduction story also began with her seeing one too many stars in the Dipper.

594
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:44,000
Even Navy pilot Ryan Graves, who's very humble in his claims, has said that pilots reported UAPs emerging from the Dipper and even dogfighting near it in orbit.

595
00:52:44,000 --> 00:52:50,000
Ancient Egyptian rituals used Dipper-shaped tools to send pharaohs into the afterlife.

596
00:52:50,000 --> 00:52:54,000
Taoist sages would trace its stars in ascension rituals.

597
00:52:54,000 --> 00:53:04,000
Ptolemy, one of the fathers of modern astronomy in 2nd century AD Alexandria, would also say that souls would ascend through Orion's belt.

598
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:10,000
Even the Thule Society saw the circumpolar stars as a point of origin for non-human intelligences.

599
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:14,000
And then look at modern super-experiencers like Chris Bledsoe.

600
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:23,000
Bledsoe believes that the non-human intelligence he is in contact with, which he has termed the Lady, is linked to the Dipper.

601
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:28,000
And that her companions call themselves, quote unquote, the Guardians.

602
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:32,000
Coincidentally, Guardians is the term now used by the US Space Force.

603
00:53:32,000 --> 00:53:41,000
And the emblem of Space Delta-7, the Space Force's intelligence wing, shows a bear holding a key in front of the Big Dipper.

604
00:53:41,000 --> 00:53:44,000
So we return to the central question.

605
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:46,000
Are these patterns just coincidence?

606
00:53:46,000 --> 00:53:49,000
Are we connecting the dots in a crazy way?

607
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:52,000
Pareidolia, finding patterns where they don't exist.

608
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:56,000
Or does the pattern these disparate dots create suggest something deeper?

609
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:10,000
We return to Diana Pasolka in her discussions with the enigmatic Tyler D.

610
00:54:10,000 --> 00:54:13,000
Timothy Taylor, the NASA mission controller.

611
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:21,000
One of the most curious aspects of Taylor's story is his claim that he receives downloads from an intelligence he believes is non-human.

612
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:27,000
These downloads appear as sudden flashes of insight, full mental blueprints or instructions.

613
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:33,000
He says they come to him through specific protocols and they've led to real patents and technologies.

614
00:54:33,000 --> 00:54:39,000
They have also shaped how he approaches his ongoing work within the US space program.

615
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:46,000
Even if we take the most skeptical approach, assuming Taylor is simply a high ranking engineer with strange personal beliefs,

616
00:54:46,000 --> 00:54:50,000
it still leaves us with a wild but undeniable fact.

617
00:54:50,000 --> 00:54:56,000
Someone overseeing major NASA launches believes they are influenced by a non-human intelligence.

618
00:54:56,000 --> 00:55:01,000
I'm fairly sure Tim Taylor is a known entity at Kennedy Space Center.

619
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:05,000
I personally tried to meet up with him once, but he had to go to Florida for a launch.

620
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:13,000
And finally, I've found this bizarre connection between Tim Taylor and mid-century anti-gravity inventor Thomas Townsend Brown.

621
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:20,000
Brown's daughter Linda reviewed Tim Taylor's book on Amazon before anybody knew who Tim Taylor was,

622
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:26,000
well before he was written about even pseudonymously in Diana Posulka's American Cosmic.

623
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:35,000
And then Tim Taylor apparently told Christopher Bledsoe's son Ryan that he was part of a secret time travel program in Nassau in the Bahamas,

624
00:55:35,000 --> 00:55:40,000
and that Thomas Townsend Brown was the president of that group.

625
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:46,000
I know a ton about Thomas Townsend Brown, and I can tell you definitively he was obsessed with time travel.

626
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:55,000
He also spent an inordinate amount of time in the Bahamas with the inspiration for James Bond and Winston Churchill's super spy, William Stevenson.

627
00:55:55,000 --> 00:56:01,000
And then there's Tim Taylor telling Posulka that he was part of the quote-unquote adjustment team,

628
00:56:01,000 --> 00:56:06,000
an homage to Philip K. Dick's great book about a team of time travelers.

629
00:56:06,000 --> 00:56:12,000
And if we're going to entertain this speculation for a second, then how would a secret time travel program actually work?

630
00:56:12,000 --> 00:56:16,000
We know in general relativity that gravity and time are highly related.

631
00:56:16,000 --> 00:56:20,000
So maybe you'd do an experiment like Thomas Townsend Brown's.

632
00:56:20,000 --> 00:56:25,000
You might create a high-voltage environment that bends spacetime itself.

633
00:56:25,000 --> 00:56:33,000
Or you might launch a very oddly timed rocket that happens to coincide with ancient traditional rituals.

634
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:39,000
Who knows? I doubt we'll ever know.

635
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:42,000
But even if you dismiss all of those crazy theories,

636
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:46,000
it is clear that the modern space program is not just a technical story.

637
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:52,000
It's a story about consciousness, belief, and the role of the human mind in space exploration.

638
00:56:52,000 --> 00:56:56,000
This same theme shows up in other unexpected places.

639
00:56:56,000 --> 00:57:02,000
Take James Ryder, former vice president of Lockheed Martin, and a director at Skunk Works.

640
00:57:02,000 --> 00:57:05,000
In 2018, he gave a talk called The Garment of God.

641
00:57:05,000 --> 00:57:12,000
In it, he emphasized the relationship between mysticism, consciousness, and technological progress.

642
00:57:12,000 --> 00:57:16,000
In a separate lecture focused entirely on UAPs,

643
00:57:16,000 --> 00:57:19,000
